            <p class="section-intro">Answers to common questions about pursuing a career in Nanotechnology:</p>
            
            <div class="accordion">
                <div class="accordion-item active">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What educational background is needed for nanotechnology?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>A bachelor's degree in Physics, Chemistry, Materials Science, or Engineering provides a good foundation. Specialized knowledge in quantum mechanics, materials science, and fabrication techniques is essential. Advanced roles in R&D typically require a master's or PhD in Nanotechnology or a related field. Interdisciplinary knowledge spanning multiple scientific domains is highly valuable in this field.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">How does nanotechnology differ from other engineering fields?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>Nanotechnology is uniquely focused on understanding and manipulating matter at the nanoscale (1-100 nm), where materials exhibit quantum effects and novel properties. Unlike traditional engineering disciplines, it's inherently interdisciplinary, combining elements of physics, chemistry, biology, and engineering. Nanotechnology engineers work at the atomic and molecular level to create materials and devices with unprecedented capabilities.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What are the key industries for nanotechnology professionals?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>Nanotechnology professionals work in diverse sectors including semiconductor and electronics, pharmaceuticals and biotechnology, advanced materials manufacturing, energy (solar cells, batteries), aerospace, and defense. Research institutions, government laboratories, and startups focused on nanotechnology innovations also offer significant opportunities. The field continues to expand into new industries as applications develop.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">How can I start learning nanotechnology?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>Begin with courses in physics, chemistry, and materials science to build a strong foundation. Learn specialized topics like quantum mechanics, surface science, and nanofabrication techniques. Gain hands-on experience through laboratory work with nanomaterials synthesis and characterization equipment. Join professional organizations like the Nano Science and Technology Consortium (NSTC) for networking and resources.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="accordion-item">
                    <div class="accordion-header">What are the career growth prospects?</div>
                    <div class="accordion-content">
                        <p>Nanotechnology offers strong career prospects with growing demand for innovations across multiple industries. Career paths typically progress from research scientist or process engineer to senior researcher, project leader, or technical specialist. With experience, opportunities exist in technology management, intellectual property development, or entrepreneurship in nanotechnology startups. The field's interdisciplinary nature allows professionals to pivot between different application areas as the technology evolves.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
